On International Holocaust Remembrance Day, the author reflects on the importance of remembering the 6 million Jews, as well as other groups, who were murdered during the Holocaust. They recall their personal connection to the Holocaust through their father's stories and emphasize the need to pass on the history to future generations. The author condemns Holocaust deniers and highlights the rise of anti-Semitism and bigotry in today's world. They mention the events in Charlottesville in 2017 as a reminder of the ongoing need to combat hatred and prevent future genocides. The author concludes by affirming the United States' commitment to justice for Holocaust survivors and their dedication to building a world where the lessons of the Holocaust are valued and all human lives are respected.